de.polygonal.ds.ArrayedDeque<T>

type
class
implements
Deque<T>

A deque ("double-ended queue") is a linear list for which all insertions and deletions (and usually all accesses) are made at ends of the list.

Constructor

new(?blockSize : Int, ?blockPoolCapacity : Int, ?maxSize : Int)

parameters
blockSize a block represents a contiguous piece of memory; whenever the deque runs out of space an additional block with a capacity of blockSize elements is allocated and added to the existing blocks.
The parameter affects the performance-memory trade-off: a large blockSize improves performances but wastes memory if the utilization is low; a small blockSize uses memory more efficiently but is slower due to frequent allocation of blocks.
The default value is 64; the minimum value is 4.
blockSize has to be a power of two.
blockPoolSize the total number of blocks to reuse when blocks are removed or relocated (from front to back or vice-versa). This improves performances but uses more memory.
The default value is 4; a value of 0 disables block pooling.
maxSize the maximum allowed size of this deque.
The default value of -1 indicates that there is no upper limit.
throws
de.polygonal.core.util.AssertionError invalid blockSize (debug only).

Instance Variables

key : Int

A unique identifier for this object.
A hash table transforms this key into an index of an array element by using a hash function.
This value should never be changed by the user.

maxSize : Int

The maximum allowed size of this deque.
Once the maximum size is reached, adding an element will fail with an error (debug only). A value of -1 indicates that the size is unbound.
Always equals -1 in release mode.

Instance Methods

assign(C : Class<T>, ?args : Array<Dynamic>, ?n : Int) : Void

parameters
C the class to instantiate for each element.
args passes additional constructor arguments to the class C.
n the number of elements to replace. If 0, n is set to size().
throws
de.polygonal.core.util.AssertionError n > maxSize (debug only).
Replaces up to n existing elements with objects of type C.
If size() < n, additional elements are added to the back of this deque.

inline back() : T

throws
de.polygonal.core.util.AssertionError deque is empty (debug only).
Returns the last element of the deque.

clear(?purge : Bool) : Void

parameters
purge if true, elements are nullified upon removal. This also removes all superfluous blocks and clears the pool.
Removes all elements.

clone(assign : Bool, ?copier : T -> T) : Collection<T>

parameters
assign if true, the copier parameter is ignored and primitive elements are copied by value whereas objects are copied by reference.
If false, the clone() method is called on each element. In this case all elements have to implement Cloneable.
copier a custom function for copying elements. Replaces element.clone() if assign is false.
throws
de.polygonal.core.util.AssertionError element is not of type Cloneable (debug only).
Duplicates this deque. Supports shallow (structure only) and deep copies (structure & elements).

contains(x : T) : Bool

Returns true if this deque contains the element x.

fill(x : T, ?n : Int) : Void

parameters
n the number of elements to replace. If 0, n is set to size().
Replaces up to n existing elements with the instance of x.
If size() < n, additional elements are added to the back of this deque.

free() : Void

Destroys this object by explicitly nullifying all elements for GC'ing used resources.
Improves GC efficiency/performance (optional).

inline front() : T

getBack(i : Int) : T

de.polygonal.core.util.AssertionError deque is empty (debug only).
de.polygonal.core.util.AssertionError index out of range (debug only).
Returns the element at index i relative to the back of this deque.
The back element is at index 0, the front element is at index [size() - 1].

toString() : String

Returns a string representing the current object.
Prints out all elements if compiled with the -debug directive.
Example:

	  var deque = new de.polygonal.ds.ArrayedDeque<Int>();
	  for (i in 0...4) {
	      deque.pushFront(i);
	  }
	  trace(deque);
	  {ArrayedDeque, size: 4}
	  |< front
	    0 -> 3
	    1 -> 2
	    2 -> 1
	    3 -> 0
	  >|
